FARCASTER LOGIN

What is Farcaster good for?

It’s good for devs.
It’s good for data analysts.
And it’s good for social login.

The last is the thing I’m most interested in. 

When you start a new site you can use Google or Apple login. And that’s fine. But it just gives you an email. And maybe Google Drive access in Google’s case.

You can also use X/Twitter, Facebook, or LinkedIn. But those APIs change so quickly and adversarially that you can’t really build features on your site that rely on them. So you end up using them similarly to Google login, where you get a username only.

Now arrives Farcaster. The first fairly large scale decentralized crypto social protocol. Where people aren’t in it solely for the money.

Now, for all users who log in with Farcaster, suddenly you can provide encrypted messaging between accounts and pull their full social context. And if they’ve connected a wallet and ENS, they have a balance and can spend and receive money in your app.

This changes everything.

Did you know that honeybees have a unique and fascinating way of communicating with each other? They use a dance known as the "waggle dance" to convey crucial information about the location of flowers and food sources to their fellow bees in the hive. In this dance, the worker bee waggles its body in a specific pattern that includes the direction and distance of the food source relative to the position of the sun. Other bees carefully observe this movement and then fly to the indicated location to collect nectar and pollen. This method of communication highlights the sophisticated and organized social life of honeybees, as well as the importance of cooperation in ensuring the colony's survival. This phenomenon is not only astonishing but also illustrates the hidden beauty and intelligence within the natural world.

Did you know that the Emperor penguin is the only bird species that can dive to depths of over 500 meters and hold its breath for more than 20 minutes? Their extraordinary adaptations demonstrate remarkable survival skills in extreme environments. Emperor penguins have bodies specifically designed for deep dives into the cold waters around Antarctica. They possess specialized hemoglobin that allows their blood to store more oxygen, and their muscles can function efficiently even with very low oxygen levels. These adaptations not only enable them to forage in depths unreachable by many predators but also showcase the incredible and innovative ways nature creates survival mechanisms. The Emperor penguin is a testament to the marvel of biological adaptation in one of the harshest environments on Earth.

I've experienced working at a large traditional company, early stage startup, founding a fund, and founding a startup. Some random thoughts

- AIG: work hard and learn a lot but difficult to have autonomy with layers of management, most there to collect paycheck, how you stand out depends on manager

- Coinbase (30-150 employees): work hard but first time work didn't feel like work since cared deeply, tons of autonomy, first time working with many mission driven colleagues, can stand out taking initiative, did not have a sense of how hard being a founder was for Brian + Fred

- Scalar (founded fund): work harder (no days off in week), decisions fall on founders so huge sense of ownership, lows are really low, first sense of how hard things can really get

- Bountycaster (founded company): work harder than founding fund (default is work and then carve out personal time), cycles of highs and lows much more rapid than fund, feel most fulfilled due to ownership, mission, and connecting with users

i joined farcaster in 2021 after my then bf got me an invite.

i had never met dan, didn’t have any crypto twitter friends, and had always been v private on social media.

i casted with sincerity about anything and everything, reported bug after bug, and began to host and show up to meetups where everyone was shocked to learn i was a woman.

it was obvious to me that we weren’t building social media, but a social network. 

and, if successful, it wouldn’t be just one network, but a network of networks.

whenever someone asked me why i loved farcaster so deeply, i’d reply that it had the highest signal:noise ratio.

then permissionless happened, then frames, then degen.

the signal:noise flipped. i abruptly boycotted.

the issue is that boycotting is inherently inaction. but me? i have always had a bias for action.

3 days later, i was back on FC.

3 months later, i led FarCon alongside an incredible group of casters.

and now, half a year later, i’m still here building.

this is how we win together.

a year ago, i woke up miles from lahaina burning to the ground.

thousands lost their homes, a hundred lost their lives.

i lost nothing except for a carefree vacation, which is nothing relative to everything.

we spent the week in red cross evacuation centers and, when they were full, we slept under the stars in the bed of the pickup truck.

sixteen year old me would have reveled at the charm of a spontaneous surf trip to hawaii. if only she knew the circumstances, i thought to myself one night.

why do we so often romanticize that sense of freedom, that connection to nature over the very real physical discomfort one can only feel from awkward hours pressed against the cold, unrelenting ridges of a truck’s metal frame?

i smile, knowing the answer. comfort is no match for human’s desire for what is primal and raw.

i feel something hit my forehead, then my bare shoulder. my eyes shoot open. the silhouette of trees sway under moonlit clouds beginning to burst with rain. 

i close my eyes. 

i feel it all.

My Farcaster conspiracy theory is that the small pause in between clicking "cast now" and your post going live serves a different purpose. On Twitter, you can send 150 tweets per minute and get lost in the adrenaline rush. But FC forces you to think about your life in between casts. 

You can take those 15 seconds while your cast is booting up to ask yourself really solid questions:

- Should you continue to live in SF?
- Should you have aped into memecoins and ditched bad research tokens?
- Should you still launch a project with plans to dump on users?
- Will AGI kill us all?

So, breathe, and look outside the window while creating casts. It's your small chance to get some sanity back into your daily routine. Farcaster is good for your mental health.

Here are some tips for creating a powerful bio:

*Be concise and clear: Use words that convey your core message.

*Inspire with your unique value: Show what sets you apart from others.

*Use relevant keywords: This makes you easier to find on search platforms.

*Add a call-to-action: Like a link to your website or latest project.

*Don’t be afraid to use humor: A funny touch can humanize your bio and make people smile.

*Keep it up-to-date: Adjust your bio as your goals or interests change.

A strong bio attracts the right followers and sets the tone for how people perceive you. You have 31 characters—make each one count!
